body:
ETA: Third post summarizes the problem.

I'm trying to migrate from `EF Core 6` to `EF Core 8` and have run into a problem I cannot get past without a hack.  I'm not sure how `dotnet-ef` works, so this could be a [Pomelo](https://github.com/PomeloFoundation/Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql) issue.  The problem was raised on [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/78220889/after-upgrading-from-net-6-to-net-8-getting-results-json-ambiguous-call) in March, without an answer.

I've recreated the problem with 2 files here:

## TestContext.csproj
```XML
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <Target Name="PreBuild" BeforeTargets="PreBuildEvent" Condition="'$(BuildingInsideVisualStudio)' == 'true'">
    <Exec Command="dotnet-ef dbcontext optimize -c TestContext --framework net8.0" />
  </Target>

  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design" Version="8.0.8" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Tools" Version="8.0.8" />
    <PackageReference Include="Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql" Version="8.0.2" />
    <PackageReference Include="Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql.Json.Microsoft" Version="8.0.2" />
    <PackageReference Include="System.Text.Json" Version="8.0.4" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
```

## TestContext.cs
```C#
using System.Text.Json;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.ChangeTracking;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Metadata.Builders;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Storage.ValueConversion;

namespace TestContext
{
    #region Model

    public class CustomProperty
    {
        public string Key { get; set; } = "";
        public string Value { get; set; } = "";
    }

    public class WorkOrder
    {
        public int Id { get; set; }
        public ICollection<CustomProperty>? CustomProperties { get; set; } = [];
    }

    #endregion

    #region Mapping

    public class WorkOrderMap : IEntityTypeConfiguration<WorkOrder>
    {
        public void Configure(EntityTypeBuilder<WorkOrder> builder)
        {
            builder.ToTable("t_work_order");
            builder.Property(t => t.Id).HasColumnName("work_order_id");
            builder.Property(t => t.CustomProperties).HasColumnName("custom_properties")
                .HasColumnType("json")
                .HasConversion<WorkOrderCustomPropertiesConverter, WorkOrderCustomPropertiesComparer>()
            ;
        }
    }

    // via https://stackoverflow.com/a/73719507/158502
    internal class WorkOrderCustomPropertiesConverter : ValueConverter<ICollection<CustomProperty>?, string>
    {
        public WorkOrderCustomPropertiesConverter()
            : base(v => JsonSerializer.Serialize(v, (JsonSerializerOptions)null),
             v => JsonSerializer.Deserialize<HashSet<CustomProperty>>(v, (JsonSerializerOptions)null),
             null)
        { }
    }

    // via https://stackoverflow.com/a/73719507/158502
    internal class WorkOrderCustomPropertiesComparer : ValueComparer<ICollection<CustomProperty>?>
    {
        public WorkOrderCustomPropertiesComparer()
            : base((c1, c2) => c1.SequenceEqual(c2),
                    c => c.Aggregate(0, (a, v) => HashCode.Combine(a, v.GetHashCode())),
                    c => c.ToHashSet())
        { }
    }

    #endregion Mapping

    #region Context

    public class TestContext : DbContext
    {
        private readonly string? _connectionString = "port=3306";

        public TestContext() { }

        public TestContext(string connectionString)
        {
            _connectionString = connectionString;
        }

        protected override void OnConfiguring(DbContextOptionsBuilder optionsBuilder)
        {
            optionsBuilder.UseMySql(
                _connectionString,
                new MySqlServerVersion("8.0.21"),
                mySqlOptions => mySqlOptions
                    .UseMicrosoftJson(MySqlCommonJsonChangeTrackingOptions.FullHierarchyOptimizedSemantically)
            );
        }

        protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
        {
            base.OnModelCreating(modelBuilder);

            modelBuilder.ApplyConfiguration(new WorkOrderMap());
        }

        public DbSet<WorkOrder> WorkOrders { get; set; }
    }

    #endregion Context
}
```

If you build once, `CompiledModels` get generated as part of the `PreBuildEvent`. However, once the `CompiledModels` are generated, the next build will fail because `CompiledModels` were generated with code that does not compile:

```C#
                converter: new ValueConverter<ICollection<CustomProperty>, string>(
                    (ICollection<CustomProperty> v) => MySqlJsonMicrosoftStringValueConverter.ConvertToProviderCore(JsonSerializer.Serialize(v, null)),
                    (string v) => JsonSerializer.Deserialize<HashSet<CustomProperty>>(MySqlJsonMicrosoftStringValueConverter.ConvertFromProviderCore(v), null)));
```

Compilation Error:
```
Severity	Code	Description	Project	File	Line	Suppression State
Error	CS0121	The call is ambiguous between the following methods or properties:
'JsonSerializer.Serialize<TValue>(TValue, JsonSerializerOptions?)' and
'JsonSerializer.Serialize<TValue>(TValue, JsonTypeInfo<TValue>)'
TestContext	C:\...\TestContext\CompiledModels\WorkOrderEntityType.cs	74	Active
```

## Resolution
Is this expected? Am I doing something wrong?  Perhaps misusing `HasConversion`? The code runs fine before CompiledModels are introduced. This approach also works fine in .NET 6.0, because the `valueConverter` and `valueComparer` are honored and this new `converter:` property/argument is not introduced.

It also coincidentally works if I'm not storing a collection, but an object instead.

## Hack Fix
I can hack-fix this by running a script after `dotnet-ef` to change the usage of `JsonSerializer.Serialize` to pass either `JsonSerializerOptions.Default` or `(JsonSerializerOptions)null`:

EF Core version: 8.0.8
Database provider: Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql
Target framework: .NET 8.0
Operating system: Windows 11
IDE: Visual Studio 2022 17.9.5
dotnet-ef version: 8.0.8
